04191nam a22005175i 9780226357973DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015038316  a9780226357973  a(DE-B1597)549962  a(OCoLC)1229161613  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aE175.4.W9bG75 2016 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a0282231 aGriswold, Wendy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Guides :bThe Federal Writers’ Project and the Casting of American Culture /cWendy Griswold. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b9 halftones, 5 maps, 2 line drawings, 45 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the midst of the Great Depression, Americans were nearly universally literate—and they were hungry for the written word. Magazines, novels, and newspapers littered the floors of parlors and tenements alike. With an eye to this market and as a response to devastating unemployment, Roosevelt’s Works Progress Administration created the Federal Writers’ Project. The Project’s mission was simple: jobs. But, as Wendy Griswold shows in the lively and persuasive American Guides, the Project had a profound—and unintended—cultural impact that went far beyond the writers’ paychecks. Griswold’s subject here is the Project’s American Guides, an impressively produced series that set out not only to direct travelers on which routes to take and what to see throughout the country, but also to celebrate the distinctive characteristics of each individual state. Griswold finds that the series unintentionally diversified American literary culture’s cast of characters—promoting women, minority, and rural writers—while it also institutionalized the innovative idea that American culture comes in state-shaped boxes. Griswold’s story alters our customary ideas about cultural change as a gradual process, revealing how diversity is often the result of politically strategic decisions and bureaucratic logic, as well as of the conflicts between snobbish metropolitan intellectuals and stubborn locals. American Guides reveals the significance of cultural federalism and the indelible impact that the Federal Writers’ Project continues to have on the American literary landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFederal Writers' Project - Influence. 0aRegionalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSocial changezUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  asociology, great depression, literacy, magazines, newspapers, unemployment, works progress administration, president roosevelt, fdr, federal writers project, jobs, employment, economics, economy, 20th century, us history, united states, cultural impact, american guides, travel writing, travelling, social change, politics, culture, federalism, diversity, bureaucratic logic, politically strategic decisions, regionalism, intellectual life, civilization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226357973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226357973/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles